section.section:
If the court determines from the pleadings, affidavits and admissions on file, and the evidence, if any, that the lien should not attach, or should not attach in the amount claimed, as a matter of law, by any final order, but that there is probable cause to believe the petitioner is entitled to a lien, the court shall enter an interlocutory order which:
Establishes the lien;
Describes the boundaries of the land and the buildings to which the lien attaches;
States the amount of the claim for which probable cause is found;
Specifies the amount of a bond that the owner may file to have the land and building released from the lien;
May require the claimant to file a bond in an amount that the court believes sufficient for damages, including reasonable attorney's fees; and
Assigns a date for the trial of all the matters at issue in the action, which shall be within a period of six months. The owner or any other person interested in the property, however, may, at any time, move to have the lien established by the interlocutory order modified or dissolved.
